76561197998490461,Recommended,217200,9616820,"Posted: 24 March, 2014",all,cheep crybabby hatter,"The best worms game.The Worms franchise is a very good idea executed very similarly over and over again. You have a bunch of cute little worms, with cute little physics-based weapons (well, sometimes they're not so little), trying to destroy each other. It's brilliant because it's ridiculously fun for both casual and hardcore gamers. The hardcore gamers get their kicks from practising their technique until they become unstoppably accurate with all their shots, whereas the causal gamers simply enjoy the trial-and-error fun of shooting bazookas at each other.That's the entire Worms franchise. All the Worms games are more or less like this: quality games that are more or less interchangeable. That being said, I would have to say that Worms Armageddon is the best Worms game so far. It has a wide variety of weaponry, a huge capacity for customisation (although you need to beat the game to get the full options), very accessible level editor, interesting missions, training that is actually fun, as well as a ""deathmatch"" mode that is fun, intense, and has never since been replicated.Although these are petty concerns, where WA falls short is in two respects: a slight lack of help in how to play the game, and in its online community. I found that, when I first played WA (when it came out), it was difficult to figure out all the little controls. There are two jump buttons, and pressing or double pressing produces different jumps, which was confusing at first. Also, customising grenades, such as changing the fuse time or making them bouncy, was never clearly explained. If you buy this game, consult the following page:http://wormsarmageddon.team17.com/main.html?page=abou&area=contMost of the necessary controls you can pick up in the game, but the page is a useful reference when you really want to nail down your grenade shots or your ninja roping.The other problem, as I mentioned, was the online community. When last I checked, WA had an entrenched and hostile online community, where the standard was absurdly high, and anyone not of this standard was abused and/or dropped from games. But, so long as you play with friends, this shouldn't be a problem."
